Explanation of results and reasoning:

- The Admin\PostController class implements an edit(Post $post): View method that returns the server-rendered view 'admin.posts.edit'. According to Laravel conventions, this method is used to display an edit form for a specific Post model instance.
- The controller method signature indicates that the endpoint is path-parameterized by a Post model instance, so the path parameter name is "post" and it is required. Typical Laravel Post models use numeric primary keys; therefore the path parameter is documented as an integer (int64).
- The method returns a View (server-rendered HTML). Therefore the successful response content type is text/html; the schema for that media type is a string (format: html).
- The view is passed three pieces of data: 'post' (the Post model being edited), 'users' (a keyed list of authors), and 'media' (a keyed list of media). I included this in the operation description so clients understand what the rendered view will have available.
- A 404 response is possible if the route-model binding does not find the Post, so a 404 response entry is provided with a short description (no response body schema).
- I set an operationId matching the controller and method (AdminPostController_edit) and used a concise summary from the controller docblock.

